{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 19:39:50.507393", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of network health\n- Overall status: Degraded. User hosts cannot obtain IP addresses and therefore have no connectivity. Additionally, the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is OSPF-isolated from the rest of the network due to missing adjacencies on the server-access side.\n- Impact:\n  - End-user hosts (host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1) have no IP configuration, cannot reach DNS or HTTP services.\n  - Even if hosts had IPs, routes to/from the server farm are not being exchanged with the core/distribution due to OSPF adjacency failures between server_access_router and the core (via router_core_3).\n\nKey observations and evidence\n1) End hosts lack IP configuration (DHCP failure)\n- host_1_1_1_1: Interface up but no IPv4 address and empty routing table (no default route).\n  - ip addr/route shows no IP on eth0; ip route is empty.\n  - Pings from host_1_1_1_1 to any server (LB or web servers) and even DNS all return “Network is unreachable.”\n  - curl tests to web99.local/web0.local return near-zero timing values, indicating immediate failure (no DNS/route).\n- host_2_1_1_1: Same symptoms: eth0 up, no IP address, no routes; pings fail with “Network is unreachable.”\n\n2) DHCP infrastructure status\n- DHCP server (dhcp_server):\n  - Service isc-dhcp-server: Active (running).\n  - Listening on UDP 67 (netstat shows 0.0.0.0:67).\n  - dhcpd.conf contains correct scopes for 10.1.1.0/24, 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24 with correct default gateways and DNS (10.200.0.2).\n- Distribution routers (DHCP relay responsibility):\n  - router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1: isc-dhcp-relay is inactive (dead) and unconfigured.\n  - /etc/default/isc-dhcp-relay shows SERVERS=\"\" and INTERFACES=\"\" on both routers.\n  - No evidence of any active relay process; status is inactive and ps shows none.\n  - ARP tables on the dist routers show the expected host MACs, indicating L2 path to hosts is fine.\n\n3) OSPF routing state\n- Distribution layer OSPF: Up and exchanging with core_1/core_2.\n  - router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1 show full OSPF neighbors on uplinks and have routes for access subnets and core links.\n  - They do NOT have a route to 10.200.0.0/24—server farm network is missing in their tables.\n- Server access side (server_access_router and router_core_3):\n  - server_access_router OSPF:\n    - Config includes 10.200.0.0/24 and 172.16.0.14/31 in area 0.\n    - show ip ospf neighbor: 0 neighbors.\n    - show ip route: only connected routes present (10.200.0.0/24 via br0, and 172.16.0.14/31 on eth7); no learned routes to 10.1/10.2 subnets.\n    - show ip ospf interface: both br0 and eth7 are “State DR,” “Neighbor count 0.”\n  - router_core_3 OSPF:\n    - Config includes its core links and the 172.16.0.14/31 server-access link in area 0.\n    - show ip ospf neighbor: 0 neighbors (no adjacency with core_1, core_2, or server_access_router).\n    - show ip ospf interface (eth0, eth1, eth2): all interfaces show “State DR,” “Neighbor count 0.”\n    - show ip route: only connected 172.16.0.x routes; no 10.200.0.0/24 or access networks.\n- L3 connectivity across the server access link is physically fine:\n  - Pings between server_access_router (172.16.0.15) and router_core_3 (172.16.0.14) succeed in both directions.\n- Core OSPF elsewhere:\n  - router_core_1 and router_core_2 have a full adjacency with each other and with their respective distribution neighbors.\n  - Neither shows adjacency to router_core_3.\n\nDetected anomalies\n- DHCP relay services are down and unconfigured on both distribution routers:\n  - isc-dhcp-relay inactive (dead) on router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1.\n  - Empty SERVERS and INTERFACES in /etc/default/isc-dhcp-relay on both devices.\n- OSPF adjacencies are missing between:\n  - router_core_3 and router_core_1 (on 172.16.0.2/31).\n  - router_core_3 and router_core_2 (on 172.16.0.4/31).\n  - router_core_3 and server_access_router (on 172.16.0.14/31).\n- As a result, server_access_router has no OSPF-learned routes to user subnets and distribution routers have no route to 10.200.0.0/24.\n\nFault localization\n- DHCP failure localized to distribution routers:\n  - router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1 (DHCP relay layer) are the point of failure preventing host DHCP requests from reaching the central server.\n- OSPF isolation localized to the core segment involving router_core_3 and server_access_router:\n  - router_core_3 forms no OSPF adjacencies at all (to core_1/core_2/server_access_router), despite L3 reachability. This isolates the server farm from the rest of the OSPF domain.\n  - server_access_router shows OSPF enabled on interfaces but zero neighbors.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Root cause 1 (end-host connectivity): DHCP relay misconfiguration/disabled on both distribution routers.\n  - Evidence: isc-dhcp-relay inactive; SERVERS and INTERFACES empty on both dist routers.\n  - Effect: Hosts do not receive IP addresses or default routes, producing “Network is unreachable” for all tests.\n- Root cause 2 (server farm routing): OSPF adjacency failures on router_core_3 and server_access_router.\n  - Evidence: Both show 0 OSPF neighbors; server_access_router’s routing table contains only connected routes; router_core_3 has no adjacencies to core_1/core_2; distribution routers lack route to 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - Physical connectivity is fine (ICMP succeeds), so the fault is in OSPF neighbor formation (protocol-level). This prevents exchange of routes between the server farm and the core/distribution areas.\n\nAdditional relevant findings\n- Server farm internal connectivity is healthy: server_access_router can ping dns_server, web_server_0–3, and load_balancer inside 10.200.0.0/24.\n- iptables on server_access_router and router_core_3 default ACCEPT; no obvious filtering blocking OSPF.\n- OSPF configuration present on the correct subnets; however, adjacencies do not form on all router_core_3 interfaces, indicating a systemic OSPF neighbor formation issue on/around router_core_3 and server_access_router.\n\nConclusion\n- The network is presently unable to serve end hosts:\n  - Primary: DHCP relay is down on distribution routers, so hosts cannot obtain IPs.\n  - Secondary: OSPF adjacencies on the server-access side are not forming, isolating the server farm from the rest of the OSPF domain. Even with host IPs restored, end-to-end reachability to the servers would still fail until OSPF adjacency between router_core_3 and its neighbors (including server_access_router) is established and 10.200.0.0/24 is advertised into the domain.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 32736, "output_tokens": 7506, "total_tokens": 40242, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 32256}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 5760}}}
